So, you want to raise money for your start-up? Here are 7 factors founders need to consider:⁠
⁠
1. Passion: Some of the most successful brands were told “no” countless times before their ultimate success. Have passion for what you do!⁠
2. Demonstration: You need an initial proof of concept for investors to show your idea is viable.⁠
3. Sizeable Market: Attracting investors requires not only a great product but a large market that it appeals to.⁠
4. Team: Delegating your tasks appropriately is the best way to move forward effectively.⁠
5. Competitive Edge: You need to know what makes you stand out from the competition, more than simply “wanting it more.”⁠
6. Plan of Action: Be aware of unit economics and ensure your projections are realistic.⁠
7. YOU: Investors care about the person behind a company. Are you showcasing yourself in the right light? Are you doing personal branding to help you stand out?⁠
⁠
Unless you’re independently wealthy, all startups start with funding, and as a founder, it’s important to know what will help you move forward! Do you have any other factors to add to my list?

Do you know how to market yourself on LinkedIn? If you don’t already have a strategy, it’s time to create one.⁠

Does your personal brand statement need a revamp? Keep reading for some tips that will help.⁠
⁠
Simply put, you should always follow this equation when writing your brand statement: Your Action, Your Target Client, and Your Solution.⁠
⁠
Let me break it down a bit more:⁠
⁠
👉️ Your Action: This portion of your statement involves choosing the right starting word, such as “I help…” or “I build…” to convey to your audience that you are able to solve their problems. ⁠
👉️ Your Target Client: When you pinpoint your specific audience with titles like “Entrepreneurs” or “Tech Startup Founders,” a reader will quickly be able to identify whom you help.  However, if you want your statement to be less aggressive, you can use vague terms like “Customers” or “Clients.” I made this conscious decision because my clients hate anything salesy or pushy. ⁠
👉️ Your Solution: This section needs to identify your ideal audience’s pain point and what you do to fix it. ⁠
⁠
With this formula, your personal brand statement will attract more ideal clients and make your brand stand out.⁠
⁠

Navigating the social media landscape involves mastering the delicate balance of celebrating wins without turning them into a "yay me" post. There’s a thin line between celebration and show-off. My take: go beyond the win. ⁠
⁠
For instance, instead of a plain "Closed a deal" announcement, share the strategy that clinched it. Adding a twist of storytelling—share the journey, the struggles, and the lessons—transforms a mere win into a valuable insight. After all, people crave more than a highlight reel; they yearn for the captivating behind-the-scenes action.⁠
⁠
Try these instead:⁠
⁠
➡️ Share the Strategy: Rather than a plain announcement, delve into the strategies that led to your success.⁠
➡️ Storytelling Matters: Transform a mere win into a valuable insight by sharing the journey, struggles, and lessons learned.⁠
➡️ Blend Celebration with Substance: Historically, there has been a strong preference for posts that seamlessly integrate celebration with valuable content. ⁠
⁠
So, brag if you must, but make it a good story worth celebrating. What's your take on striking the balance between showcasing wins and not sounding like a broken record?⁠
